Random Number generation is covered in zyBooks 2.18. In your
own words, explain the effect of passing the result of the time
function as an argument to srand(). Why is this commonly done in
programs that use random number generation?
• Be specific, and if you’d like, you may include a short code example to
support your explanation.

Srand is used to set the seed for the random number genrator, 
to increase the "randomness" of the number generated. For example, 
assuming the programmer imported the proper time #include, one could
set up the srand() to include a random generator based on the time, 
which would constantly shift, and avoid having the same seed. If the seed
is the same for each generation, programmers run the risk of ruining the user
experience of using the random number, which could accidentally rig something
like a coin toss. Since the random number generates based on the seed, if the seed 
is the same, the random output will be the same.